{"id":1574,"date":"2024-05-10T06:36:04","date_gmt":"2024-05-10T06:36:04","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.skillvertex.com\/blog\/?p=1574"},"modified":"2024-05-10T06:36:04","modified_gmt":"2024-05-10T06:36:04","slug":"in-which-type-of-storage-replication-data-is-not-replicated-across-multiple-data-centers-in-azure","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.skillvertex.com\/blog\/in-which-type-of-storage-replication-data-is-not-replicated-across-multiple-data-centers-in-azure\/","title":{"rendered":"In Which Type Of Storage Replication, Data Is Not Replicated Across Multiple Data Centers In Azure?"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">In Which Type Of Storage Replication, Data Is Not Replicated Across Multiple Data Centers In Azure?<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Answer. <\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>In Azure, when using Locally Redundant Storage (LRS), data is not replicated across multiple data centers. LRS provides a level of redundancy by creating multiple copies of your data within the same data center. However, it does not replicate data to different data centers in different geographical regions.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>LRS is a cost-effective option for protecting your data from local hardware failures within a data center, but it does not provide protection against a complete data center failure or a regional outage. If you require data replication across multiple data centers for higher availability and disaster recovery purposes, you would typically opt for one of the other Azure storage replication options, such as Geo-Redundant Storage (GRS) or Zone-Redundant Storage (ZRS).<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>In Which Type Of Storage Replication, Data Is Not Replicated Across Multiple Data Centers In Azure? Answer. In Azure, when using Locally Redundant Storage (LRS), data is not replicated across multiple data centers. LRS provides a level of redundancy by creating multiple copies of your data within the same data center. How